caption: Located on the corner of Rue de Verbois and Rue Saint Martin, stand this lovely fountain, built is the early 1700's, this is one of many things to see during a woalk of the 3rd Arrondissement.

The Vert Bois fountain or Saint-Martin fountain is a fountain located at the corner of rue du Vertbois and rue Saint-Martin attached to the wall of the Philippe Auguste enclosure of the former Saint-Martin-des priory -Champs, current National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts in the 3rd arrondissement of Paris

The Fontaine du Vert Bois or Fontaine Saint-Martin is a Fountain located at the corner of rue du Vertbois and rue Saint-Martin adjoining the wall of the Philippe Auguste enclosure of the former Saint-Martin-des priory -Champs, current National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts, Paris (3rd). Built at the request of Louis XIV in 1712 according to plans by Pierre Bullet. It has a large decorated pediment with a nave decorated with sails, supported by two pilasters paired in bossage using alternating vermiculated and frozen decoration. Water flows from a bronze mask with the head of an imaginary sea monster, a decorative figure often used at the time. In the middle of the fountain, a plaque commemorating its movement in 1882 is a reminder of its history. The bas-relief above the plaque represents a vessel sailing on the waves. The sculpture is itself crowned with the royal crest, crowned and winged.
Be careful, there is no water.
Former priory of Saint Martin des Champs
